{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600647/1930073101/0706.xml":{"full_text":"D. C. BANKS REPORT\nDROP IN CLEARINGS\nDecline of $18,000,000 From\n1929 Figures Is Shown\nin July.\nBY EDWARD C. STONE.\nBank clearings in the National Cap\nital in July totaled 5109.420.638.23, ac\ncording to reports made this noon by\nthe Washington Clearing House Asso\nciation. in comparison with $127,497,-\n771.87 in July, 1929, or a falling off of\n$18,077,133.64\nClearings in Washington in July were\nalso lower than in July, 1928. when they\namounted to $114,2J3,667 81, but were\nabove the figures e<!' 1927, when July\ncancelled checks reached the sum of\n$108,600,949.19. Comparisons with 1927\nand 1928 are important as 1929 was\nconsidered an abnormal year when\nclearings smashed all previous years in\nWashington as well as in most other\nplaces.\nClearings for the first seven months\nof the present year, now available, show\nthat the local clearing house canceled\n$785,670,847.81 in checks against $878.-\n545.619.05 in the first seven months of\n1929 and $825,209,993.82 in the cor\nresponding period in 1928. Back in\n1927 clearings in 'Washington totalled\n$823,040,610.03. also being larger than\nIn the same seven months of 1930.\nThe figures kept by Charles E.\nBright, manager of the Clearing House\nAssociation, show that business will\nhave to score most remarkable improve\nment during the remainder of 1930 to\nbring clearings to a total approaching\nthat of a year ago. As July is usually\nthe quietest business month in the year,\nexcept possibly February, local bankers\npredict gradual improvement during\nthe remaining five months of 1930.\nSo far in 1930 bank clearings in\nWashington have been lower each\nmonth than they were in the same\nmonth in 1929. This is true in almost\nevery other large city in the country.\nFor the first seven months of the year!\nthe Washington Clearing House records\ninclude the following comparisons, by\nmonths, with the corresponding months\nin 1929:\nJaifuary' tIISJULm *l29 9 438.291\nM.Vch\"!.:::::::: ulnflll iftnSim\nApri* 118.036.552 129.300.050\nMay 113.055.037 126.836.189\nJunV 116.290.346 124.028.347\nJuly 109,420.638 127.497.771\nTotals $785,670,847 $878,545,619\nLocal Bankers on Vacations.\nLocal bankers continue to enjoy their\nannual vacation periods and are com\ning and going at a lively pace.\nEdward J. McQuade. vice president\nof the Liberty National Bank, leaves\nhere tomorrow for New York and on\nSaturday will sail for the Pacific Coast\nby nay of the Panama Canal.\nPresident Corcoran Thom of the\nAmerican Security Trust Co. is back\nat his desk after his, trip to Europe.\nPresident H. W. Offutt of the Poto\nmac Savings Bank leaves here next\nweek for a two-we<.\u00ab. vacation at Cape\nMay.\nHarold W. Burnside, assistant man\nager of the Farmers Mechanics\u2019\nbranch of the Riggs National Bank, in\nGeorgetown, has returned from a\nmonths\u2019 vacation passed at Epplng\nForest.\nLaurence R. Lecby and August\nSchmidt, jr., of G. M. P. Murphy\nCo., will leave here this week via air\nplane lor a month's stay in Texas.\nHerbert W. Frimm. assistant real\nestate officer of the Washington Loan\nTrust Co., is motoring to Wildwood\nCrest, N. J., for a two-week vacation.\nPay Boost to Aid Trade.\nController General McCarl estimated\nthat, approximately 20,000 Government\nemployes will benefit by the recent raise\nin pay and that the total increase will\nbe about $3,160,000 ptr year.\nThe estimate is based upon the fact\nthat some 6.000 employes will receive\na raise of S6O, that probably the same\nnumber will receive an increase of SIOO\nand about the same number will receive\nan increase of S2OO, while something\nlike 2.000 will receive an increase of\napproximately SSOO.\nThis means something like $300,000\nper month which will find its way into\nsavings deposits, investment and trade\nin Washington in addition to the\namounts which have been habitually\ndispersed by th? Government and\nturned into the above channels. This\namount is certain to be a distinct help\nin the expected business revival this\nFall.\nCoffee Firm Votes Dividends.\nThe board of directors of the Dip\nlomat Coffee Co., of this city, has de\nclared the regular dividend on th\u00bb pre\nferred stock at the rate of 8 per cent\nper annum, and a dividend on the\ncommon stock at the rate of 4 per cent\nper annum. Both payable to stock\nholders of record as of July 1, on Au\ngust 15, 1930. The transfer books will\nnot be closed and checks will be mailed\nas soon as possible after this date, ac\ncording to President W. E. Smith.\nInsurance Men Plan Outing.\nThe Summer outing of the DLstrict of\nColumbia Life Underwriters Associa\ntion will take place Thursday afternoon,\nAugust 15, at the Indian Spring Golf\nClub, it was announced todey. Golf\nwill feature the afternoon and bridge\nthe evening entertainment, while the\nradio will furnish the music for danc\ning. The members will have a dinner\nat 6:30, The officers expect the largest\nattendance they have had at any of\nthese outings.\nTrading on D. C. Exchange.\nTrading was unusually quiet on the\nWashington Stock Exchange today. The\nfirst transaction was in Steamboat\nrights, which sold at 16 and later sold\nat 16%. Ten shares of Lanston Mono\ntype at 113*2. Two SSOO bond sales\nin Capital Traction 5s were recorded\nat 94*2, while SSOO Washington Gas 5s\nchanged hands at 104.\nThe vice president, Edward L. Hillyer,\nhas been presiding at recent sessions of\nthe exchange. The president, George\nO. Wals&n, is expected back from his\nVacation next Monday.\nSouthern Corporation Mails Report.\nCopies of the annual report of the\nSouthern Corporation, of which Herbert\nJ. Adair is president, were sent today\nto the stockholders. It is the first\nannual report and covers operations to\nJune 30, 1930, the company having been\nformed on July 2, 1929.\nOperations for the period from the\ndate of organization to June 30, 1930,\nthe report says, resulted in a net profit\nof $282,499.00. which is represented as\nsurplus at the beginning of the current\nfiscal period. The corporation\u2019s net\nassets amounted to $4,655,555.78. taking\nthe securities at their market value.\nThe corporation had no funded debt or\nbank loans at June 30, 1930.\nm-\nWOULD REDUCE FARES.\nCHICAGO, July 31 (A*j. \u2014Permission\nto reduce train fares between this city\nand St. Louis, to meet bus line competi\ntion, will be 8-sked of the Interstate\nCommerce Commission by the Chicago\n\u25a0to Alton Railroad, President W. C.\nBierd has announced.\n1 According to the executive, the Alton\nwould operate one reduced fare train\ndaily each way between the two points.\nBus fares for the trip range from $3\nto $5, while train fare is around $lO.\nPARIS BOURSE PRICES.\nPARIS. July 31 OP). \u2014Price changes\nwere irregular on the Bourse today.\nThree per cent rentes. 88 francs 75\ncentimes. Five per cent loan, 102\nfranen. Exchange on London, 123\nfrancs 78** centimes. The dollar wai\nat H frarirg SI V. wntlmM.\nFINANCIAL\nI NEW YORK STOCK EXCHANGE I\nReceived by Private Wire Direct to The SUr Office.\nNote\u2014All itorki are eoid In one hundred-share lota\nexcepting those designated by the letter s (655) (265a) 1\nwhich shows those seocks to be sold In odd lots only.\n--rr\u00abv.l#Bo\u2014. Slock and Sales\u2014\nHUh. Low. Dividend Roto. Add 00. HLh. Low. Close. Cloto.\n66 42 Abraham Strauoa. 1 57% 67% 67* 4<\n110 104 Abraham ASt pf (7) 20a 108 108 108 108\n374* 2IT* Adame Kxp 11.60)... 27 26% 26* 2614 26*\n92 85* Adams Expr\u2019e pf (6) 10s 91 #1 91 \u00bb1\n32 23 Adams Mlllla (5)... 2 26 26 26 26\n3444 29* Addressograph (1*) 1 81* 31'4 31* 81\n23* 8 Advance Humlev 6 11 10* 10*\n41* 15* Advance Rumley pf. 1 22 22 2-\u2019 21\n1H Mi Ahumada Leid 5 K\n156* 103* Air Reduction (1)... 45 115* 112* 115 113*\n36 16 Air Wav T1 Ap(2*>. 3 18 1714 17* 18\n2* 1 Ajax Rubber 2 1* 1* I**\n.9* 4* Alaska Juneau 1 5* 5* 5* 5*\n35